---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<BaseLayout title="Troparion Cards" description="Printable troparion and kontakion cards for the major feasts of the Byzantine liturgical year.">

  <section class="article-hero">
    <div class="hero-content">
      <div class="section-label" style="margin-bottom:16px;">Practical Tool</div>
      <h1 class="hero-title" style="font-size:34px;">Troparion Cards</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        The hymns that define each feast — print them, learn them, pray them.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="article-surface">
    <div class="container--narrow">
      <nav class="breadcrumbs">
        <a href={`${base}/`}>Home</a>
        <span class="sep">›</span>
        <a href={`${base}/tools/`}>Tools</a>
        <span class="sep">›</span>
        <span style="color: var(--beeswax);">Troparion Cards</span>
      </nav>

      <article class="article-body">

        <p class="drop-cap">Every feast day in the Byzantine tradition has two essential hymns: the <strong>troparion</strong> and the <strong>kontakion</strong>. The troparion states the theological meaning of the feast. What happened. Why it matters. The kontakion responds, often from the perspective of those who witnessed it. Together: a miniature catechism set to music, everything needed to understand a feast compressed into a few lines.</p>

        <p>Below are the troparia and kontakia for the eight greatest feasts. Print them. Tape them to the prayer corner. Carry them during the feast season. They are meant to be memorized, not as rote exercise, but because these words, repeated day after day, teach the faith from the inside out.</p>

        <p class="print-instruction">🖨 <strong>To print:</strong> Use your browser's print function (Ctrl+P / Cmd+P). The cards are designed to print two per row on standard letter paper. Cut along the dotted lines.</p>

      </article>

      <div class="cards-grid">

        <div class="troparion-card">
          <div class="card-feast-header">
            <span class="card-feast-name">The Nativity of Christ</span>
            <span class="card-feast-date">December 25</span>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Troparion — Tone 4</div>
            <div class="card-text">Your Nativity, O Christ our God, has shone to the world the light of wisdom; for by it, those who worshipped the stars were taught by a star to adore You, the Sun of Righteousness, and to know You, the Orient from on high. O Lord, glory to You!</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Kontakion — Tone 3</div>
            <div class="card-text">Today the Virgin gives birth to the Transcendent One, and the earth offers a cave to the Unapproachable One. Angels with shepherds glorify Him; the wise men journey with a star; since for our sake the Eternal God was born as a little Child!</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-note">The Incarnation: God enters creation through a cave, a mother, and the smallness of an infant. The star teaches the astrologers to worship not the heavens, but the One who made them.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="troparion-card">
          <div class="card-feast-header">
            <span class="card-feast-name">Theophany</span>
            <span class="card-feast-date">January 6</span>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Troparion — Tone 1</div>
            <div class="card-text">When You, O Lord, were baptized in the Jordan, the worship of the Trinity was made manifest. For the voice of the Father bore witness to You, calling You His beloved Son, and the Spirit in the form of a dove confirmed the truthfulness of His word. O Christ our God, You have revealed Yourself and have enlightened the world, glory to You!</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Kontakion — Tone 4</div>
            <div class="card-text">Today You have shown forth to the world, O Lord, and the light of Your countenance has been marked on us. Knowing You, we sing to You: You have come and revealed Yourself, O Unapproachable Light!</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-note">The Baptism of Christ in the Jordan — the Trinity revealed: the Father's voice from heaven, the Son in the waters, the Spirit descending as a dove. The feast of light.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="troparion-card">
          <div class="card-feast-header">
            <span class="card-feast-name">The Transfiguration</span>
            <span class="card-feast-date">August 6</span>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Troparion — Tone 7</div>
            <div class="card-text">You were transfigured on the mountain, O Christ God, revealing Your glory to Your disciples as far as they could bear it. Let Your everlasting Light also shine upon us sinners, through the prayers of the Theotokos. O Giver of Light, glory to You!</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Kontakion — Tone 7</div>
            <div class="card-text">On the mountain You were transfigured, O Christ God, and Your disciples beheld Your glory as far as they could see it; so that when they would behold You crucified, they would understand that Your suffering was voluntary, and would proclaim to the world that You are truly the Radiance of the Father.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-note">On Mount Tabor, Christ's divine glory shines through His human body — "as far as they could bear it." The light the disciples saw is the same uncreated light that awaits all who pursue theosis.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="troparion-card">
          <div class="card-feast-header">
            <span class="card-feast-name">The Dormition of the Theotokos</span>
            <span class="card-feast-date">August 15</span>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Troparion — Tone 1</div>
            <div class="card-text">In giving birth you preserved your virginity; in falling asleep you did not forsake the world, O Theotokos. You were translated to life, O Mother of Life, and by your prayers you deliver our souls from death.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Kontakion — Tone 2</div>
            <div class="card-text">Neither the tomb nor death could hold the Theotokos, who is constant in prayer and our firm hope in her intercessions. For being the Mother of Life, she was translated to life by the One who dwelt in her virginal womb.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-note">The "falling asleep" of the Mother of God — not death as ending, but passage into fuller life. She did not "forsake the world" — her prayers continue.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="troparion-card">
          <div class="card-feast-header">
            <span class="card-feast-name">The Elevation of the Cross</span>
            <span class="card-feast-date">September 14</span>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Troparion — Tone 1</div>
            <div class="card-text">O Lord, save Your people and bless Your inheritance. Grant victories to the faithful over adversaries, and by the virtue of Your Cross, preserve Your habitation.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Kontakion — Tone 4</div>
            <div class="card-text">As You were voluntarily raised upon the Cross for our sake, grant mercy to those who are called by Your name, O Christ God. Make all faithful people glad by Your power, granting them victories over adversaries by bestowing on them the invincible trophy, Your weapon of peace.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-note">The Cross is not defeat but victory — an "invincible trophy" and "weapon of peace." The feast commemorates the finding of the True Cross by St. Helena in Jerusalem (4th century).</div>
        </div>

        <div class="troparion-card">
          <div class="card-feast-header">
            <span class="card-feast-name">Pascha</span>
            <span class="card-feast-date">The Feast of Feasts</span>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Troparion — Tone 5</div>
            <div class="card-text">Christ is risen from the dead, trampling down death by death, and upon those in the tombs bestowing life!</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Kontakion — Tone 8</div>
            <div class="card-text">Though You descended into the grave, O Immortal One, You destroyed the power of Hades and rose as victor, O Christ God, calling to the myrrh-bearing women: Rejoice! And giving peace to Your apostles: Peace to you who have fallen grant resurrection.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-note">The Resurrection — the center of everything. "Trampling down death by death": Christ enters death itself and destroys it from the inside. This troparion is sung hundreds of times during Bright Week.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="troparion-card">
          <div class="card-feast-header">
            <span class="card-feast-name">The Ascension</span>
            <span class="card-feast-date">40 days after Pascha</span>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Troparion — Tone 4</div>
            <div class="card-text">You ascended in glory, O Christ our God, granting joy to Your disciples by the promise of the Holy Spirit. Through the blessing they were assured that You are the Son of God, the Redeemer of the world.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Kontakion — Tone 6</div>
            <div class="card-text">When You had fulfilled the dispensation for our sake and united earth to heaven, You ascended in glory, O Christ our God, not being parted from those who love You, but remaining with them and crying: I am with you, and no one will be against you!</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-note">Christ ascends — but does not leave. "United earth to heaven": human nature is now at the right hand of the Father. He remains with those who love Him.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="troparion-card">
          <div class="card-feast-header">
            <span class="card-feast-name">Pentecost</span>
            <span class="card-feast-date">50 days after Pascha</span>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Troparion — Tone 8</div>
            <div class="card-text">Blessed are You, O Christ our God, You have revealed the fishermen as most wise by sending down upon them the Holy Spirit; through them You drew the whole world into Your net. O Lover of Man, glory to You!</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-section">
            <div class="card-label">Kontakion — Tone 8</div>
            <div class="card-text">When the Most High came down and confused the tongues, He divided the nations. But when He distributed the tongues of fire, He called all to unity. Therefore, with one voice we glorify the All-Holy Spirit.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-note">Pentecost reverses Babel. Where the tower divided languages and scattered nations, the Spirit unites them. Fishermen become theologians — not by education, but by fire.</div>
        </div>

      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .article-hero {
    padding: 80px 40px 32px;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .article-body {
    padding-bottom: 16px;
  }
  .article-body p {
    font-size: 17px;
    line-height: 1.85;
    color: var(--aged-vellum);
    margin-bottom: 20px;
  }
  .article-body .drop-cap::first-letter {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 56px;
    float: left;
    color: var(--halo-gold);
    opacity: 0.7;
    line-height: 0.8;
    margin: 8px 14px 0 0;
    font-weight: 400;
  }
  .print-instruction {
    font-family: var(--font-ui);
    font-size: 13px;
    color: var(--censer-smoke);
    background: var(--gold-04);
    padding: 12px 16px;
    border-radius: 8px;
    margin-bottom: 32px;
  }

  /* Cards grid */
  .cards-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    gap: 20px;
    padding-bottom: 80px;
  }

  .troparion-card {
    background: var(--icon-wall);
    border: 0.5px solid var(--gold-10);
    border-radius: 12px;
    padding: 28px;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 16px;
  }

  .card-feast-header {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: baseline;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 8px;
    padding-bottom: 12px;
    border-bottom: 0.5px solid var(--gold-10);
  }
  .card-feast-name {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 20px;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--beeswax);
  }
  .card-feast-date {
    font-family: var(--font-ui);
    font-size: 11px;
    color: var(--halo-gold);
    letter-spacing: 0.5px;
  }

  .card-section { }
  .card-label {
    font-family: var(--font-ui);
    font-size: 9px;
    letter-spacing: 1.5px;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--deep-muted);
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }
  .card-text {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: 15px;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--aged-vellum);
    font-style: italic;
  }
  .card-note {
    font-family: var(--font-ui);
    font-size: 12px;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--censer-smoke);
    padding-top: 12px;
    border-top: 0.5px solid var(--gold-06);
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .cards-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }

  /* ========== PRINT STYLES ========== */
  @media print {
    body {
      background: white !important;
      color: black !important;
    }
    .article-hero,
    .breadcrumbs,
    .print-instruction,
    nav,
    footer {
      display: none !important;
    }
    .article-body {
      padding-bottom: 8px;
    }
    .article-body p {
      color: #333;
      font-size: 11pt;
    }
    .cards-grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
      gap: 0;
      padding-bottom: 0;
    }
    .troparion-card {
      background: white;
      border: 1px dashed #999;
      border-radius: 0;
      padding: 16px;
      page-break-inside: avoid;
    }
    .card-feast-header {
      border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc;
    }
    .card-feast-name { color: #111; }
    .card-feast-date { color: #555; }
    .card-label { color: #666; }
    .card-text { color: #222; font-size: 10pt; }
    .card-note { color: #555; border-top: 1px solid #ddd; font-size: 9pt; }
    .container--narrow { max-width: 100%; padding: 0 8px; }
  }
</style>
